What is Enterprise Integration?
      It is a process of combining multiple separate enterprise software together into one system.  Consider in modern bank system, what happens when you pay with your bank card,
   - payment is processed on a terminal and information is sent to Central banking system and back signaling that you have enough money to make a purchase
   - simultaneously Central banking system sends notification to your mobile
application so that you get a popup message, if you then request your bank statement at bank's website or at its office, you will get an updated information, accounting for your latest purchase    	As we can see there is a lot of different software systems, terminal, Central banking system mobile application, website and many more, all this systems need to communicate information and
Enterprise Integration is a process of enabling that communication 

What is Apache Camel ?
     Apache camel was created to solve exactly this kind of problem integration, it is
an opensource Java framework designed specifically for building integration solutions, it allows developers to set up integrations that connect systems, convert data formats, perform
transformations, handle errors and login, handle different communication protocols like HTTP, JMS and many others, camel does this with a concept called routes which moves data from one system to another.
    When you request your bank statement at your bank's office, here camel is used to connect Banks office software to the Central banking system, imagine that the bank's office software is a bit old and can only communicate by JMS protocol with XML messages, while Central banking system is more modern and communicates by HTTP protocol and Json messages, here is how camel comes into play 
    Banks office software sends a JMS statement request, this request is read by camel route from
a JMS Queue then it is logged and then transformed from XML to Json and that Json is then used as HTTP request to the central banking system. Json response from the central banking system is then
transformed back from Json to XML and then this statement response is sent back as a JMS message to the bank's office software, so with camel you  find these kinds of routes to define a
flow of data between systems

What is Apache Camel? -  three bullet points which i took it from the camel website itself
1. Apache camel is an open source integration framework that empowers you to quickly and easily integrate various systems consuming or producing data
2. Apache camel is a versatile open source integration framework based on known
enterprise integration patterns 
3. Apache camel is the industry standard for reducing boilerplate code for complex integrations while maintaining features like automatic error handling re-delivery of policies the ability to handle complex aggregations

These points are quite simple straightforward plain english but one thing you notice here is that there is a one common point which is called integration

What is Integration?
1. Integration of different systems
      Integration means integration of different systems so when we say different systems, you can have different operating systems (ie) one running on windows platform and other running on unix  based platform still you would like these systems to communicate to each other.
2. Integration of different technologies
      Integration of different technologies maybe one system is using some sort of tcp based protocol, another one using maybe another protocol like udp, doesn't really matter but still we like to communicate using those different technologies 
3. Different systems working together 
     One system maybe erp system, another is maybe some sort of chat system you like to send a notification ,maybe email system you like to send emails some sort of notifications
all these systems working together in harmony 
4. Different programming languages   
     The system can be written in java, .net, c-sharp, php, python doesn't really matter but still
you like to talk to that system, you like to exchange data with that system 
5. Different message formats 
     Maybe your system is producing json or my system only understands xml still we like to talk to each other and we like to exchange the data 

So this is know on a high level what integration means, you are trying to talk to another system
written in another language using different technology running on different platform, it's quite a complex problem in in enterprise sector

What is Enterprise Integration Pattern?
      It is a catalog of design patterns for developing systems to integrate new and existing software in a business environment 

Why do you need Integration Patterns ?
1. Different software has different formats
        As we discussed you know different software has different formats, one is using json another using xml, third maybe some very native like protocol buffer 
2. when you're integrating you don't know whether it is point-to-point integration or hub and spoke integration

Point to Point integration - Expensive 
      We have three system at the top are trying to talk to the bottom three systems, you can see in point-to-point integration every system  have one line coming from itself to the 
system which it's trying to integrate, so you can see first system is talking to three different systems. Imagine if first system has to talk to rest of these systems it will have five arrows.
    If we try to bring a new system, we can see the lines will become six, another one seven. Imagine if every system started to talk to each other, it is kind of a cartesian product, so if we have like six system maybe we need 36 integration, so the complexity just grows out of control. 
    If there is any critical  change in one system then all other systems which are connected to it will break until they are ready to take those changes, that's why it's called like quite an expensive integration pattern

Hub and spoke integration
     You have a hub sitting in between, all these systems which are around it they are publishing messages to this hub or receiving messages from this
     Easy to understand and easy to implement
     Typically Hub can be some sort of enterprise bus or some sort of messaging system like ibm mq, rabbitmq, kafka or it can be a simple file system where somebody putting a file and other parties is reading file or it can be a database one party is writing database and maybe other are reading from database 

These are two typical integration patterns which fall into either point to point or hub & spoke, so what other types are there in the enterprise design pattern. They created 65 design patterns and categorize into seven categories like

1. Messaging systems - you can send email or you can send usome sort of soap or you canconstruct json or you can send xml it doesn't really matter so it basically explains how you can use messaging systems to send the message 
2. Messaging channels -  you can have a point to point queues, you can have a publish subscribe topics, message bus 
3. Message construction - so when we are constructing a message where should you put the data, where should you put the headers, where should you put the additional properties etc
4.  Message Routing - Routing of message, you can have a content-based routing (ie) you have a message either by looking at the message or looking at the header we can decide where to route that message 
5. Message transformation - how should you be transforming your message, aggregation
was one of those things. So you get the data from bunch of upstream systems, you took those pieces of data and enriched with some useful information, to get a new message 
6. Message endpoints - where your systems basically connect or talk to other system using some sort of layer in between 
7. System management - how should we managing system, suppose i want to bring one system down or we  would like to do some upgrades etc

In our example we were using patterns like message, it is our message that is read from jms queue, transformed sent to banking system and then back message Channel, these are our
