Apache Camel Architecture
      A main component is camelcontext which holds all camel related entities, these entities are routes which represents data flows between systems, components which allow camel to communicate with various software by various protocols, endpoints which are message channels through which messages are sent and received, processor which modify messages and execute any user defined logic, registry which serves as a storage for many camel related entities and many other
components 

1. CamelContext
       Camel context is the most important part of Apache camel framework. CamelContext is a
runtime which makes all these entities work together, most importantly it runs our routes which means that without camelcontext our Integrations will not start to be ready for running

Lifecycle of CamelContext
1. First camelcontext is created by using DefaultCamelContext, it is used when we have a
standalone camel application without spring framework 
2. Then all necessary entities like routes are added to the context 
3. Then context is started and all routes that were added at configuration step start working, receiving and sending messages 
4. When we don't want to run our integrations or routes anymore we stop the context and all routes stop working
5. Finally we should close the context 

By the way camelContext implements Autocloseable interface which means that we can use try with resources to close it automatically

2. Routes
       They specify how data is transferred from one system to another, we write camel routes
using camel's domain specific languages or dsls, for now there are three dsls available Java DSL, XML DSL and yaml DSL
      Each camel route is a series of steps that will be executed with our data. 

from("file:src/main/resources/files").routeId("example-roure")
     .log("File contains: ${body}")
     .transform().simple("File contents: ${body}")
     .to("file:src/main/resources/files/processed");


- Each camel route starts with from() DSL element which specifies a source or input for our route, for example 
     from("file:src/main/resources/files")

The input for this route will be some file located in the specified directory. Similarly
     from("jms:queue:statementRequest")
The input for this route will be statementRequest JMS queue. In this from() statement technically we can pass any string here, but not any string will work for example if we write something
like my custom component here it will not work. only those strings that have camel component associated with them can work 
    
- After the from() statement one or more processing steps follow, these steps are DSL elements that do something with our message or execute some logic. For example, we can see log processing step displays the message and transform processing steps changes the message content

- Last processing step in this route is to() DSL element which sends the message to some destination, in our case this destination is a file system directory 
- Each camel route has its own ID, we can specify it in routeId DSL element, if we don't do it camel will generate one automatically

3.  Message 
        Camel works with messages as they flow through camel routes, messages are data records
that are used by different systems to communicate with each other. 
       Camel message is an abstraction that can represent something like JMS, Kafka message, HTTP request or file in a file system. 
       It consists of body, headers. Body is a payload of the message, it can be of any type and
length. Next headers  represents an additional information attached to the message, it has a type of java.util.map of strings (ie) each camel header has a unique name of type string and can have any value 
       Next MessageId is a message identifier, usually camel generates this message ID by itself, but some components provide their own message IDs. Lastly camel message may or may not have
a timestamp associated with it, similar to messageID some camel components can provide a time stamp, but like messageID this time stamp is not generated by camel automatically, it must
be provided by 

4. Camel Exchange
       Normally  messages do not flow through camel routes by themselves, they are contained
within camel exchanges. In apache camel, exchanges represent request and optionally a response message or an exception that happened during processing of the request. We can think of exchange as of container for message and some metadata that is flowing through camel route 
       Camel exchange contains exchangeID which is a unique identifier of an exchange generated by
camel itself,  exception is Java exception that might be thrown during a flow of camel route, pattern is a flag that indicates if this exchange is used for request reply or event messaging,
properties and variables are maps containing different metadata similar to headers in message and exchange clock is a Java object that might be used to obtain a time stamp of exchange creation
       MEP(Message Exchange Patterns) - There are two types of messages we can have like inonly or inout 
InOnly - manadatory - one-way message also known as event message, so you're sending something you don't care about like what happened to that message. 
InOut - optional - We are sending something and we want either some sort of response back from

So in MEP you define what sort of data this exchange holds in message either inonly or inout message

5. Camel Components
       Components are connectors that allow camel to communicate with external systems, they provide connectivity to many different protocols or software elements such as Kafka, JMS, HTTP and many others. Components are what we use in our camel routes from() and to() statements in order for them to work. 
       So how we know what to specify in from() and to(), for example how do we know that
we need to write file then colon and then the directory, there is only one place to get
this information official camel documentation https://camel.apache.org/components/, we find the list of all available components 
       So if we need to read the file, so we will go to "file" component description and first thing that we can see here is exactly the string that we were using in our camel route, file then
colon and then directory name 

6. Camel Endpoints
       Camel end points are an abstraction over message Channel integration pattern, each camel endpoint represents such Channel through which different systems can exchange messages.
       In our example route, we have two end points, from() file endpoint that reads files from specified directory and to() file endpoint that writes file to another directory.
       from end point is called a consumer because it reads or consumes messages in our files, as
they arrive to end point it is called a producer because it writes or produces messages to the specified destination. 
       Different end points can represent different things, for example HTTP consumer endpoint would act as a HTTP server as it will read incoming HTTP messages, HTTP producer Endpoint would act as a HTTP client and it will send HTTP messages to the specified URL. JMS consumer endpoint will read JMS messages from queue or a topic, as they arrive JMS producer endpoint will write
or publish JMS messages to queue or a topic.
      Now we see how end points are created in camels internally, endpoints are produced by
components. For example, in our route what actually happens internally is that camel sees this
file part of the string in from() and goes to file component and asks for an object which will read files from the specified directory, this object is our consumer
     The same happens in our to() statement,camel sees this file part goes to file component except this time it asks for an object that will write files to the specified directory and that's how we get our producer file endpoint 
     So Camel endpoints represent message channels and it is the end points who actually read and
write messages and components are used only to produce these end points 

7. Processor
       Processors are used to perform custom logic in camels routes, for example transform message body, log message contents or add or modify headers. Camel provides many built-in processors for
example log processor for logging, transform processor for changing message body etc.
      Additionally you can implement your own processors by implementing Processor interface which
has only one method process() used to execute our business logic 




