3. Create route using file component which reads file from this input directory, logs it and writes it to output directory with the same name

@Component
public class ProcessorExampleRoute extends RouteBuilder {
    @Override
    public void configure() {
        from("file:src/main/resources/files?fileName=processor-example.txt&noop=true")
                .log("Body: ${body}, Headers: ${headers}")
                .to("file:src/main/resources/files/output?fileName=processor-example.txt");
    }
}

4. Now we do message mapping using process() DSL element which takes a Processor in implementation and only has one method process() that can implement any logic like transformation of our message

 public void configure() {
        from("file:src/main/resources/files?fileName=processor-example.txt&noop=true")
                .log("Body: ${body}, Headers: ${headers}")
                .process(exchange -> {
                    //First extract our message with getMessage() and then we need to extract a body from our message with getBody(), as our message is read by file component it will have a generic file type but we can specify String.class and camel will do transformation by extracting file contents and putting them into the string
                    String body = exchange.getMessage().getBody(String.class);

                   //we transform our message body to uppercase 
                    String transformedBody=body.toUpperCase();

                    //we need to write our new transformed body to our message using setBody()
                    exchange.getMessage().setBody(transformedBody);
                })
                .to("file:src/main/resources/files/output?fileName=processor-example.txt");
    }

In general all camel transformations with process() DSL and processors follow the same sequence, first we extract our body headers, message properties, variables all that we need, then we use any Java  concept to transform them and then we write them back to the exchange 

