11. handled() and continued() DSL Elements
          In onException block we mark an exception as handled(), this means that Camel will
count the error as processed normally and will not forward it to error handlers

.onException(Exception.class)
    	   .log("Exception: ${exception}")
    	   .maximumRedeliveries(2)
    	   .redeliveryDelay(300)
    	   .handled(true)
    	.end()

- Run the appl, since our exception is marked as handled and this is why we don't see any stack traces, camel does not count it as an error anymore, and an exception object is deleted from our
message, but the message processing does not continue it stops at the step that caused an exception 

- But in rare case we want to continue processing our message as normal after we dealt with our
exception, we can use continued() DSL element this means that after this exception processing steps message routing will continue

.onException(Exception.class)
    	   .log("Exception: ${exception}")
    	   .maximumRedeliveries(2)
    	   .redeliveryDelay(300)
    	   .continued(true)
    	.end()

- Run the appl, now we can see exception and "Ended route with body: Hello World" message also, this is because after continued we went further to our next processing step


