Variables vs Properties
1. Properties have only exchange scope, but variables can have an exchange scope and global scope which means variable is global for the whole camelcontext 

2. Variables can be used with variable send() and receive() DSL element 

3. Variables can have custom scope which means that you can use any custom implemented storage for variable you want, for example you might store your variables in database and share them even between different camel applications

4. Camel properties are used internally by camel, for example if your property is called something like HTTP_Headers, you might have an unexpected behavior as some Camel HTTP components might look
into this property to configure their behavior 

So always use variables instead of properties, most of the time they have different scopes, they can be stored in custom location like database and shared between different camel applications, they have variable send and variable receive DSL support and finally variables are not
used internally by camel components so you don't have a chance of overriding


