Multicast EIP with SpringBoot & Apache Camel.
    Multicast EIP allows to route the same message to a number of endpoints and process them in a different way.
    So we have incoming message but we have multiple receipent list (ie) different endpoints, and we are sending copy of this message to these endpoints and once these endpoints modify that message with some additional information and those changes will not be visible to other endpoints 
    For example, we have news portal so based on ur region it can translate the news in ur own regional language. So consider we have content management system where storywriter is writing in english, as soon as that person submits the story it can come to server and the server can broadcast to multiple endpoints which are responsible to translate that into regional language, this is where we can use Multicast EIP
    Similarly in e-commerce appl, as soon as customer places an order, we can broadcast the order to several enpoints like allocating the stock, notify the warehouse, shippment the items etc

1. Create route 

So if we are not using multicast EIP, then we send request to multiple endpoints like
  from(“ “)
     .to(“direct:A”,”direct:B”);

Here it sequentially send message from one endpoint to another endpoint. So the problem here is that if endpoint “A” modifies any message those changes will be reflected on endpoint “B”

But our requirements is that when we receive a message we need to broadcast that message either sequentially or parallelly since multicast supports both, but we dont want that message to be modified on other endpoints

- So we are going to use timer which sends some orders for every 2sec. Next we update the body of message by representing order in json format and orderid with incremental value


@Component
public class MultiCastRoute extends RouteBuilder{

	@Override
	public void configure() throws Exception { 

//we are going to use timer which sends some orders for every 2sec
		from("timer:orders?period=2000")

//Next we update the body of message by representing order in json format and orderid with incremental value
		   .process(exchange ->exchange.getIn().setBody(
                                                "{order-id: '"
                                                        + (orderId.getAndIncrement())
                                                        + "', "
                                                        + "price: '£20.00'}"))

//Now we want to send order to payment and stock-allocation endpoints
           .to("direct:payment", "direct:stock-allocation");

//Once we receive the message in payment endpoint, we need to modify it and print the data
from("direct:payment").process(exchange -> enrich(exchange, "Paid")).log(LoggingLevel.ERROR, "${body}");
        
//After payment has been taken,stock has been allocated and we need to publish an event to notify other routes
from("direct:stock-allocation")
                .process(exchange -> enrich(exchange, "Allocated"))
                .log(LoggingLevel.ERROR, "${body}");
	}

//user defined method to modify the data, we take json message and add new property called “status”
	 private void enrich(Exchange exchange, String statusValue) {
        Message in = exchange.getIn();  //get the message
        String order = in.getBody(String.class); //get the body of message
        String status = "'status': '" + statusValue + "'";
        String body = order.replace("}", ", " + status + "}"); //add a new value status
        in.setBody(body);
    }
}


- Run the appl, we can see status will be keep on adding into the same message for every 2sec rather on fresh copy
{order-id: '100', price: '£20.00', 'status': 'Paid'}
{order-id: '100', price: '£20.00', 'status': 'Paid', 'status': 'Allocated'}

- To avoid this problem we use Multicast EIP using multicast() DSL element

from("timer:orders?period=2000")
		.process(exchange ->exchange.getIn().setBody(
                                                "{order-id: '"
                                                        + (orderId.getAndIncrement())
                                                        + "', "
                                                        + "price: '£20.00'}"))
		.multicast()  
		.to("direct:payment", "direct:stock-allocation");

- Run the appl, now we can status will be adding to new message where we can see different routes
route2      : {order-id: '123', price: '£20.00', 'status': 'Paid'}
route3      : {order-id: '123', price: '£20.00', 'status': 'Allocated'}

So now we have send messages sequentially to different endpoints 

- Right now it is happening sequential order, eventhough camel sends fresh copy of message to these endpoints, but still are happening in sequential manner. Consider when we come to payment endpoint and if there is some delay in that endpoint, so stock-allocation will be executed only if payment is completed in that case we can use parallelProcessing() to execute them parallelly 

from("timer:orders?period=2000")
		.process(exchange ->exchange.getIn().setBody(
                                                "{order-id: '"
                                                        + (orderId.getAndIncrement())
                                                        + "', "
                                                        + "price: '£20.00'}"))
		.multicast().parallelProcessing()  
		.to("direct:payment", "direct:stock-allocation");

- Run the appl, we can say it executes in parallelly by seeing the timestamp, eventhough without parallel processing also it would be same, but if we put some sleep() we can see the difference 


